review: (all books get 5 stars)Wow. It took me a long time to read this, but I am so glad I did. Somehow Clark managed to make nearly 1000 pages of close deta(all books get 5 stars)Wow. It took me a long time to read this, but I am so glad I did. Somehow Clark managed to make nearly 1000 pages of close detail of Plath's short life as interesting as any novel. Mostly what I knew about Plath before this was about angry poetry and suicide. I have such a different image now, of a truly brilliant, hard-working, complicated woman far ahead of her time. I found her both inspiring and mystifying. Her mental illness was desperately misunderstood and mismanaged and you can't help but feel the spectacular, horrifying frustration of watching it take over her final weeks. Impossible not to wonder what might have been. Highly recommended....more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: An essential book for anyone wanting to live vegan. Explores all aspects of vegan nutrition with common sense, practical advice, countering the strangAn essential book for anyone wanting to live vegan. Explores all aspects of vegan nutrition with common sense, practical advice, countering the stranglehold social media idealists have over the vegan image. The authors readily admit that there are a number of diets for optimal health and there is no reason to pretend that veganism is the perfect diet for every body. Instead, veganism is a philosophy and ethics about how a person wants to live among their fellow creatures and should be considered on those merits. Because it involves our food, however, veganism DOES require a basic working knowledge of nutrition to be optimally healthy. This is true for all kinds of diets. This book is a marvelous handbook for those who want to embrace veganism. I wish I'd had it ten years ago....more

review: I needed this new look at the Hobbes vs Rousseau debate. Just about everyone today believes (or wants us to believe) that humans are selfish and nastyI needed this new look at the Hobbes vs Rousseau debate. Just about everyone today believes (or wants us to believe) that humans are selfish and nasty at their core and can only be controlled by rules and force (Hobbes). Most of the time, they have science and theology behind them to prove it. Bregman revisits famous stories and scientific studies to show that Rousseau, with his belief in human kindness, might have actually been right all along. Bregman is an engaging, accessible writer full of great stories and research and this is book we could all use right now. Five stars because it made me feel happy and made me want to let loose my optimistic, good-believing self!...more

title: Essential Labor: Mothering as Social Change
author: Garbes, Angela*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: 3.5 stars This is an important book and the prose is very, very good. I was nodding my head through the first half, and took loads of notes. But in th3.5 stars This is an important book and the prose is very, very good. I was nodding my head through the first half, and took loads of notes. But in the second half, I think Garbes’ structure is asked to carry more weight than it can handle. Her main premises, that mothering is not gendered, that it is highly skilled and essential labor, that capitalism and colonization undervalue care-giving of all kinds, are spot on. But things get a little confusing toward the end - is this also a book about immigration? Filipino culture? Women's bodies? women's pleasure? I loved just about everything she had to say, I just didn't think she tied it all together as clearly as she could have. Still, I would definitely recommend this book and know that I would have found it a lifeline as a young mother who often felt I had to justify my existence and never heard anyone articulate that my work was valuable and vital....more

title: Independent People
author: Laxness, Halldór
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: A slow, deep read that is well worth the effort. It is set in Iceland in the early 1900s, among poor sheep farmers who have been thoroughly indoctrinaA slow, deep read that is well worth the effort. It is set in Iceland in the early 1900s, among poor sheep farmers who have been thoroughly indoctrinated into the mythology of Independence. Bjartur, the main character, is a bully, a brute, and a fool as he pursues his independence, but still he maintains a measure of respect within the community even as animals, wives, and children suffer under his zeal. ( And yes, if you are American, this rings plenty of cultural bells.) It is Laxness’s quiet precision at revealing these sorrows and inequities without sentimentalizing them that make the book so profound and memorable. There’s plenty more to say about the spot-on skewering of wealthy “liberalism”, capitalism and the voracious destruction of “growth”, as well as the darkly comedic genius of the writing, but I’ll just leave it where it’s at and say, read it....more

review: I'd never read any of Gail Carriger's fiction before reading this, but from what I can gather from this book, it must be sparkly, busy, funny, and gooI'd never read any of Gail Carriger's fiction before reading this, but from what I can gather from this book, it must be sparkly, busy, funny, and good for the type of person who likes things like loud laughter and sexy werewolves. That's awesome, but it's not me. It doesn't matter much because this was a really fun (if slightly exhausting) exploration of story structure using pop culture examples (and some classic mythology). It was a bit rambly and repetitive at times, but it also gave me the clearest picture of why I resonate with some stories and not others, and why some books end perfectly and others feel like a betrayal. This is supposedly a murder mystery - and there IS a murder - but if you can't tell who did it and why within the first few chapters you've been living under a rock for awhile. The main character is a bit confusing and a little flat. Also, does John Banville even *know* any women? There are female characters in this book but I don't know what the hell they are supposed to be. review: There's so much to appreciate about this book. I learned a lot about the subtle kinds of racism that exist toward Asian Americans and presumptions andThere's so much to appreciate about this book. I learned a lot about the subtle kinds of racism that exist toward Asian Americans and presumptions and biases I own that had never been brought to my attention before. Hong has a lot of anger - understandably so - and she spares no one, least of all herself. From a reader's perspective, it may have made the book easier to digest if she had allowed some space to take a breather from that anger, but it's her book and her story and I wonder if it was cathartic to lay it all out like that. It wanders a bit toward the second half, when Hong talks in depth about her personal friendships and her experiences as an artist, but again, I picked up threads of understanding that I hadn't considered before. Overall, an important book for me to encounter....more

review: I found this short little book so helpful in understanding what myth is (hint: to call something a myth is not a pejorative) and how mythologies functI found this short little book so helpful in understanding what myth is (hint: to call something a myth is not a pejorative) and how mythologies function within culture. This is clearly not a comprehensive book, but for the casual reader I think it's a great starting point. I found it especially helpful in understanding the impulse toward religion and why modern religion can feel so confusing and dishonest. "A myth was an event which, in some sense had happened once, but which also happened all the time. ...Because of our strictly chronological view of history, we have no word for such an occurrence, but mythology is an art form that points beyond the history to what is timeless in human existence, helping us to get beyond the chaotic flux of random events, and glimpse the core of reality....Mythology is not an early attempt at history, and does not claim that its tales are objective fact. Like a novel, an opera or a ballet, myth is make-believe; it is a game that transfigures our fragmented, tragic world, and helps us to glimpse new possibilities..."...more

review: I picked this up looking for some insight into the short story form, which I got in spades. I also ended up with a glimpse into Saunders as a teacher I picked this up looking for some insight into the short story form, which I got in spades. I also ended up with a glimpse into Saunders as a teacher and person. What a gift. I already liked him from his work in Lincoln in the Bardo, but this book reveals the wise and gentle heart behind the writing. "Every human position has a problem with it. Believed in too much, it slides into error. It's not that no position is correct; it's that no position is correct for long. We're perpetually slipping out of absolute virtue and failing to notice, blinded by our desire to settle in - to finally stop fretting about things and relax forever and just be correct; to find an agenda and stick with it. What I admire most about Chekhov is how free of agenda he seems on the page - interested in everything but not wedded to any fixed system of belief, willing to go wherever the data[the truths of his characters] takes him....This feeling of fondness for the world takes the form in his stories of a constant state of reexamination. review: I read this to compliment some ideas I am gathering about narcissism and mothering and Fitch offers a decent portrayal of that. The rest of the story I read this to compliment some ideas I am gathering about narcissism and mothering and Fitch offers a decent portrayal of that. The rest of the story was disappointing, despite its readability, which is why I'm struggling with how to rate this. The journey of the child, Astrid, through foster care is predictably dire. Either California's foster care system in the 90's was *very* different from other states' systems or Fitch knows nothing about it. For sure there are bad foster parents, but as a former foster parent myself, I know there are basic housing requirements and oversights that would have prevented nearly all the situations Astrid encounters. (Fitch partially solves these problems by making her social workers inept idiots who never visit the houses where she lives.) There is a truly disturbing, overly-explicit sexual relationship with a man in his 50's and another later on, all dealt with as if Astrid is just unusually sophisticated and sexually competent. So many of the truly disturbing things that happen to Astrid are dismissed out of hand as she moves on to her next tragedy. Any one of the horrifying things that Astrid deals with would be enough for a novel. This just feels like overkill. Ugh....more

review: A long, deep exploration of an early 20th century family trying to make a go of it in the American West, always searching for the "Big Rock Candy MounA long, deep exploration of an early 20th century family trying to make a go of it in the American West, always searching for the "Big Rock Candy Mountain" around the next bend. Stegner's eye for details of the time period and his obvious appreciation for the vast landscapes of his settings make the book worth reading, but he also has a genius for understanding and explaining the uniquely American mindsets that arose out of that time and place. (One example is the protagonist's mocking reaction to the 1918 flu pandemic and its accompanying restrictions of social distancing, masks, and quarantines. It felt shockingly real and immediate though the book was written in the 1940's.) The characters are so real and well-considered it's hard to bear with them sometimes (the book is somewhat autobiographical), but ultimately worth it. It's also fascinating to read about the West before it was over-developed and exploited and Stegner has a tremendous eye for detail that makes his scenes sing. I know so much more about every day life at the turn of the last century just by reading this. There's a reason he's one of our literary treasures."To have that rush of sentimental loyalty at the sound of a name, to love and know a single place...Those were the things that not only his family, but thousands of Americans had missed. review: Omar El Akkad imagines a future United States, after the government's ban of fossil fuels lights a fire to long-simmering tensions with the Southern sOmar El Akkad imagines a future United States, after the government's ban of fossil fuels lights a fire to long-simmering tensions with the Southern states and explodes into civil war. The book was written in 2017, before the election mess and the pandemic, but it is shockingly prescient. (In looking at negative s here it seems that many of them were written in 2017 - I can't help wondering if the ideas in this book seem so far-fetched to them now.) El Akkad's global journalistic experience lends him a sharp eye and ear for the way ideologies get entrenched in people groups and how war serves to radicalize its victims rather than solve conflicts. This, to me, is the genius of the book. The plot and characters are adequately drawn, but it's this ability to show that despite its mythologies about unity and democracy, the US is made up of ideological groups that will inevitably clash as the world around them changes, that really lingers after reading. title: How the South Won the Civil War: Oligarchy, Democracy, and the Continuing Fight for the Soul of America
author: Richardson, Heather Cox
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: HCR is really, really talented at taking complex histories and making them understandable and readable for non-historians. Her premise here, that SoutHCR is really, really talented at taking complex histories and making them understandable and readable for non-historians. Her premise here, that Southern Confederate ideologies went West after the Civil War and reinvented themselves into the Cowboy Mythology of the white man on his own against the corruption of (evil) government forces, is pretty intriguing. "Mythology tells us that the theme of the American West was freedom, but the opposite was true. Like the antebellum South, society in the West was hierarchical according to race, class, and gender." (That's true of my home state of Oregon, for sure, which was founded as a state for whites only in 1859.) I was pretty fascinated about the shape this narrative took in the media (Bonanza, anyone? Little House on the Prairie?) and how completely baseless the assumption was that men were forging a trail out West by their own grit and determination. The West, HCR points out, was based on extractive economies from the beginning: gold, mining, oil, for example, and these were all mainly controlled by big businesses that relied on cheap (read: immigrant) labor that was unregulated and unprotected. Cowboys, with their dangerous, exhausting work for little pay, were more like eastern factory workers than loner heroes. It's a great read and a quick dive, but it's helpful for understanding the way that individualism and deregulation were both essential to the Confederate South and have become entrenched in modern politics today....more

review: A fictional novel - written in the style of a non-fiction account - about two real-life men, one an Israeli Jew and the other a Palestinian Muslim, whA fictional novel - written in the style of a non-fiction account - about two real-life men, one an Israeli Jew and the other a Palestinian Muslim, who find friendship after both their daughters are murdered in political conflicts. A gut-wrenching dive into the realities of the Israeli/Palestinian situation and the courage it takes to cross barriers, to see the other. McCann shows great sensitivity in retelling these stories, each person is given time and space to be honest,angry and complicated as well as inspiring. The name "Apeirogon" refers to a shape with a countably infinite number of sides, and you can feel McCann trying to turn and turn and show yet one more aspect to the story. Everything matters - the migrating birds, the traffic patterns, the clothes the bombers wore, the age of the soldier, the feeling of the hospital corridor, the mapping of the Dead Sea by a would-be priest. McCann offers us one facet after another in tiny snippets until it all builds to a densely complex picture of grief and courage as well as a passionate pursuit of peace. "Rami watched their eyes dart about. He knew the approaching arguments from the step slightly forward, the shuffle. It was, he knew, their isolation that had made them so vocal. They thrived in the grandeur of their rage. Yet underneath their masks they were riddled with self-doubt. He could sense the fear behind the clenched jaw. He almost knew the coming lines by heart. Once a terrorist always a terrorist. We didn't ask for them to blow up our children. They deny our very existence. They want to wipe us off the face of the map. review: This year I'm following the trail of women poets whose work reach out to me. I had to look hard to find Liz Berry's books for sale here in the States This year I'm following the trail of women poets whose work reach out to me. I had to look hard to find Liz Berry's books for sale here in the States but I am so glad I did. She writes of her own place and experience of the Black Country in (I believe) the West Midlands area of England. The dialect in many of the poems is ferocious (there are helpful translations) and strange to my ears, but the working class world and the longings of a young woman growing up within it are easily recognizable and relatable. (Whenever she writes of love or children, there is so much longing and tenderness it almost takes your breath away.) Tucked in to the harshness of coal mines, bodies ruined by work, and the vice of social shame, there's a bend toward the mythical and the natural world, which I love. review: I have two takes on this novel. First there is the beautiful tribute to Jewish culture and mythology (as well as Eastern Europe mythology), the (thinlI have two takes on this novel. First there is the beautiful tribute to Jewish culture and mythology (as well as Eastern Europe mythology), the (thinly disguised) religious and cultural conflict that shows a great deal of knowledge about history, a plot that keeps you turning pages, a great landscape, and characters you really want to like. It all makes for a great story which I didn't want to put down. Frustratingly, the book is also buried in an avalanche of metaphors. It's not that the metaphors are bad or poorly written, it's that there are so many of them. A little restraint would have made this book shine. The most frustrating part though is the petulance of the main character, Evike. She's mind-numbingly obtuse, stubborn, and self-destructive. I think the author wants us to believe there are reasons for this, but it is painful to read on the page. There is also a great deal of repetition. 3/4 of the book is Evike repeating to herself the same phrases, remembering the same romantic scene, and lusting after the Woodsman (he's the wounded, noble sort so I don't blame her necessarily). There are also some plot questions that I would have liked to have answered, but they are minor. My last complaint is more subjective, but there's an unnecessary amount of violence/gore. Frankly, it's just boring to read and I don't think it adds anything to the quality of the story. All in all, the novel is a fun read and I would gladly recommend it, but I think that the lost potential for it to be a great read is what makes me feel so frustrated....more

Biss writes as a mother, with a mother's perspectives and concerns, in pursuit of understanding the history of vaccination, the fears around it, the science we know and don't know, and the ways our lives are changed because of it. She is empathetic, real, curious, and human in her responses to what she uncovers. The book is not so much an argument for vaccination as an exploration of what it means to be a parent, what it means to live in community, our dependence on each other, and the real challenge of fear. author: Jemisin, N.K.*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I've talked to several people who didn't make it past the first chapters of this book and I understand that. Jemisin throws you right into a new worldI've talked to several people who didn't make it past the first chapters of this book and I understand that. Jemisin throws you right into a new world with no explanations, multiple points of view and voices (2nd person?! Who does that?) and it takes a while to figure out what is happening. But goodness, when you do, it's quite a ride! This is a world in apocalypse (aren't we all?) and the undoing of accepted norms and all the chaos and struggle that brings. Jemisin proves the point that diversity in publishing *matters*, in bringing a powerful voice able to articulate oppression and class structures and the ways people survive that. She checks all the representation boxes (all colors and classes, gay, bi, straight, trans, even polyamorous) and while I'm glad to see representation, it can also feel a bit forced. There is plenty of ugliness, including the murder of the protagonist's child (this is not a spoiler, it's the beginning of the book) and other horrors, but they are not out of sync with the harsh world of stone and earth-fury and upheaval, nor do they obscure the fact that this is good story-telling and an addicting read....more

title: The Book of Waking Up: Experiencing the Divine Love That Reorders a Life
author: Haines, Seth*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Because my family has been involved for many years with foster care and adoption, addiction is something I'm familiar with. I've seen how substance abBecause my family has been involved for many years with foster care and adoption, addiction is something I'm familiar with. I've seen how substance abuse wrecks innocent brains and is passed down through family lines, how poverty and violence and shame rot everything. So I approached Seth Haines' book about addiction and what underlies it with some trepidation. When I was done, I had mixed feelings. First, I know Seth and know his sincerity and honesty and that comes through in this book. He is unflinchingly transparent about his own pain and the coping mechanisms that led to addiction in his life. That experience gives him a clear-eyed view of the tendency we all have to turn away from Divine Love and towards things that can trap us. (Money, sex, and social media get equal treatment alongside substance and porn abuse.) He believes that the way out of these disordered affections is through communion with God, and he experiences this in a very literal sense when the wine of the Eucharist becomes the agent of healing for his addiction to wine/alcohol. (Even though Haines' theology seems closer to Catholicism in this book, the writing style is still very evangelical in its folksy reliance on the bible for any spiritual input. That may be hard for readers who are not part of the target audience.) His best insights, in my opinion, come at the end of the book, when he talks about true sobriety. He describes a 135-pound heroin addict who gets clean, but ends up gaining over 100 pounds because he's transferred his addiction to junk food. "Sober? Really?" Haines asks. "Without an approach to dependency that treats the whole person, including the underlying narratives of pain, we'll never walk in waking sobriety." This I can agree with wholeheartedly.Haines goes to great lengths to show that most of us deal with addictions of one kind or another that keeping us from connecting with Divine Love. On this level, I think the book works well and will be best for the type of people who have the money, time, and inclination to pick up a book on addiction and apply it to themselves. (Haines himself admits at one point that if you're reading the book, you are probably affluent-ish.) I do not think that Seth set out to write a manual for treating serious substance addiction or its generational effects and so I don't want to critique him too harshly on that point, but I did feel it was important to draw a distinction about who this book would be appropriate for. Personally, I would not simply hand it over to people I love who are mired in cycles of serious substance abuse and poverty. As a relatively healthy person, I can understand what he means when he says of his healing Eucharist experience, "The wine of my poison - it has become the substance of salvation," but as a mother, sister and friend of people who fight addiction daily, I had to put the book down for awhile. (He does leave a caveat for alcoholics saying they need to know their own weaknesses and do what is best for them. But I think that implies a level of health and awareness that many people I am involved with wouldn't have.)  According to the summary on the back of the book, "As Seth writes - addiction is simply misplaced adoration." I can certainly see areas in my own life where this is true and I appreciate Seth's encouragement to keep stripping away the things that obscure my connection to God, and I think this book is most appropriate for people who are in a similar place (or at least have done a good deal of work on rehabilitation, have wise support around them, and are ready and able to go deeper spiritually.)...more

title: Stamped from the Beginning: The Definitive History of Racist Ideas in America
author: Kendi, Ibram X.*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I don't feel qualified to judge the merits of this book as a history text - as I read I began to think of it more as sitting down with an intelligent,I don't feel qualified to judge the merits of this book as a history text - as I read I began to think of it more as sitting down with an intelligent, informed neighbor to hear their side of an ongoing story. It was powerful, shocking (not to discover that racism is pervasive, but to realize how much of it I've passively accepted in my life), humbling, and infuriating. Remember after the 2016 election when we were all reeling with shock and all our black friends were saying, "welcome to reality"? I understand that better now. Kendi shows in excruciating detail how racist thought has dominated American culture from the beginning and has never been expunged. But more than that, he reveals how racist beliefs FOLLOW racist policies as a way to justify them. In other words, we did not enslave Black people because we believed they were inferior. We enslaved Black people because it was economically beneficial to us - and to distance ourselves from it morally, we created a narrative that Blacks were an inferior race that needed our Christianizing and "stewardship." You can see this still at work today in social policies. It is a long book, over 500 pages, and densely written. At times, I thought Kendi wielded his labels a little too broadly, but as I said, I considered the book from the standpoint of hearing a version of my history from a necessary and informed perspective rather than a precise history (though, as I said, I'm simply not qualified to judge it on those merits.) Still, it's an outstanding, eye-opening, and disturbing work that I wish everyone could read.Recommended as an important book for all Americans....more

This account of his withdrawal from a life dependent on technology is inspiring and revealing. What's most admirable about it is his honest engagement with the dilemmas his choices lead to and his commitment to his path. I loved following his story through the seasons, getting an idea of a different kind of life. It's clear from his account that until/unless our culture changes to support it, this choice is really only for the fit and relatively young, probably for people with few or no children. But I gleaned so much from his observations and his honest wrestlings and I am applying what I can to my own life in ways that suit me. review: Powers grapples with a new/old story in this book. The old tragedy of man's insatiable consumption, and the new reality we face because of it. It's poPowers grapples with a new/old story in this book. The old tragedy of man's insatiable consumption, and the new reality we face because of it. It's powerful, disturbing, and hopeful all at the same time. The main story centers on a diverse group of people who each have powerful encounters and relationships with trees and are called in their own unique (imperfect) ways to act. There are academics and lawyers, game designers, eco-activists and terrorists, misfits and clowns, but they all take part in the slow unfolding of the future - as we all do. Powers covers the spectrum of possible responses to our future, but reminds us in the end that the earth itself has a long, long lifespan. I'll never think about trees the same way again, never see the forest with the eyes I once did. Going to be one of my best reads so far this year....more

review: Ah...what to say about this book? The writing is gorgeous and nuanced and excruciatingly intimate. The characters, for the most part, are deep and comAh...what to say about this book? The writing is gorgeous and nuanced and excruciatingly intimate. The characters, for the most part, are deep and complex and the relationships between them equally complex. The central themes, about trauma and recovery, about loving someone who cannot believe themselves worthy of love, are beautifully and thoroughly explored. I doubt I will ever forget the commitment and kindness so many people show to each other in this story. Nor will I forget the terrible pain and self-loathing that other characters live with as a result of experienced trauma. The false note - and it's a significant one - is in the back story, which is so horrific and unrelenting that it begins to feel cliche. (I did read an interview in which Yanagihara says there are fairy tale elements to the book and she expects readers to enter into the fantasy to some extent. That's helpful.) I chose to suspend belief in order to watch the unfolding of the relationships and hope that there would be healing for these characters. It's a hard read, exceedingly depressing at times, but it's a book that will stay with me a long time....more
